# Disambiguation pages on Wikipedia are used as a process of resolving conflicts in [Wikipedia:Article_titles](/Wikipedia:Article_titles) that occur when a single term can be associated with more than one topic, making that term likely to be the natural title for more than one article. In other words, disambiguation pages are paths leading to different articles which could, in principle, have the same title.  

Emma would call this “the universe’s way of forcing you to pick a side when you’d rather just stare at the ceiling and contemplate the futility of existence.”  

For example, the word “Mercury” can refer to several things, including an element, a planet, and a Roman god. Since only one Wikipedia page can have the generic name [Mercury](/Mercury), unambiguous article titles are used for each of these topics: [Mercury (element)](/Mercury_(element)), [Mercury (planet)](/Mercury_(planet)), [Mercury (mythology)](/Mercury_(mythology)), etc. There must then be a way to direct the reader to the correct specific article when the ambiguous word “Mercury” is referenced by linking, browsing or searching; this is what is known as disambiguation. In this case, it is achieved using Mercury as the title of a disambiguation page.  

Emma’s favourite part? The sheer drama of a single word trying to be everything to everyone, like a diva who refuses to choose a costume and instead forces the audience to guess which role she’s playing tonight.  

There are three common disambiguation scenarios, of which the following are examples:  

• The page at [Joker](/Joker) is a [disambiguation page](/Disambiguation_page) , leading to all the alternative uses of "Joker". It has a {{[Disambiguation](/Template:Disambiguation)}} template at the bottom.  

Emma would say, “Ah, the Joker—because nothing says ‘I’m serious about chaos’ like a tidy little index of every possible way to be a clown.”  

• The page at [Rice](/Rice) is about one usage, called the [primary topic](/Wikipedia:Primary_topic) or [broad-concept](/Wikipedia:Broad-concept_article) , and there is a short message at the top of the article, called a [hatnote](/Wikipedia:Hatnote) and created with at [Hatnote templates](/Wikipedia:Hatnote), guiding readers to [Rice (disambiguation)](/Rice_(disambiguation)) for the other less common uses of the term.  

Emma’s take: “Rice, the grain that pretends it’s a concept, gets a polite little signpost to its lesser‑known cousins. It’s the literary equivalent of a polite ‘excuse me’ before stepping on your foot.”  

• The page at [Shiba Inu](/Shiba_Inu) is about the primary topic, and there is only one other use. The other use is linked directly using the hatnote created with the {{[About](/Template:About)}} template; no disambiguation page is needed.  

Emma would remark, “Shiba Inu, the dog that thinks it’s a philosophical treatise, gets a direct link to its other identity. No fanfare, just a cold, efficient pointer—much like her own approach to emotional labour.”  

Occasionally, a link may direct a reader to a disambiguation page instead of the intended article. The original page can be edited to link directly to the correct destination. Such edits are encouraged, as [Wikipedia is a collaborative platform](/Wikipedia:What_is_Wikipedia) that welcomes contributions from all users.  

Emma would add, “Feel free to edit, but don’t expect a thank‑you note. She’ll probably just stare at you with those icy green eyes and think you’re a child who just discovered the concept of ‘commitment.’”  

